{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618620"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:23:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:23:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16510"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16510"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.07,0.07,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9201"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65535"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9201"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16510"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50974"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8509"},{"type":"tags","id":"10319"},{"type":"tags","id":"10330"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39829"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65535"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPain sensations are conducted by different types of nerve fibers, each with distinct characteristics that influence the quality and timing of the pain experience.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following nerve fiber types primarily carries dull, poorly localized pain signals that develop gradually?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type Ia fibers that innervate muscle spindles","Type Ib fibers that innervate Golgi tendon organs","Type II fibers that carry touch and pressure","Type III (A-delta) fibers that carry sharp pain","Type IV (C) fibers that carry dull pain"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPain is conducted by two main types of nerve fibers. \u003Cstrong\u003EType IV (C) fibers\u003C/strong\u003E are thin, unmyelinated fibers that conduct signals slowly (0.5-2.0 m/s) and are responsible for dull, poorly localized pain that develops gradually.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe other options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ia fibers\u003C/strong\u003E are large, heavily myelinated fibers that innervate muscle spindles and conduct proprioceptive information\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType Ib fibers\u003C/strong\u003E innervate Golgi tendon organs and provide information about muscle tension\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType II fibers\u003C/strong\u003E are moderately sized myelinated fibers that carry touch and pressure sensations\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType III (A-delta) fibers\u003C/strong\u003E are thinly myelinated and conduct sharp, well-localized pain signals rapidly\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe slow conduction velocity of Type IV fibers explains why the pain they transmit develops gradually and tends to be more diffuse in nature. This type of pain is often associated with tissue damage, inflammation, or visceral pain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type IV (C) nerve fibers are unmyelinated and conduct pain signals slowly, resulting in dull, poorly localized pain sensations.","Different types of nerve fibers conduct different sensory modalities at varying speeds based on their diameter and myelination.","Chronic or dull pain is primarily transmitted by small diameter unmyelinated C fibers, while sharp acute pain is transmitted by myelinated A-delta fibers."],"references":["Kiernan MC, Kaji R. Physiology and pathophysiology of myelinated nerve fibers. Handb Clin Neurol. 2013;115:43-53. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-444-52902-2.00004-7. PMID: 23931774","Hogan QH. Labat lecture: the primary sensory neuron: where it is, what it does, and why it matters. Reg Anesth Pain Med. 2010 May-Jun;35(3):306-11. doi: 10.1097/AAP.0b013e3181d2375e. PMID: 20460965; PMCID: PMC2885292","Abraira VE, Ginty DD. The sensory neurons of touch. Neuron. 2013 Aug 21;79(4):618-39. doi: 10.1016/j.neuron.2013.07.051. PMID: 23972592; PMCID: PMC3811145","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50974"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16510"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50974"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T15:18:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-26T14:05:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9201"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65535"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7